  <main id="main-doc">
    <section class="main-section" id="introduction">
      <header>Introduction</header>
      <article>
      <p>Python is a popular programming language known for its simplicity and versatility. It is widely used in web development, data science, automation, and more.</p>
      <p>Python's syntax is designed to be easy to read and understand, which makes it an excellent choice for beginners and professionals alike.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Python was created by Guido van Rossum and first released in 1991.</li>
        <li>It is an interpreted, high-level, and general-purpose programming language.</li>
        <li>Python emphasizes code readability with the use of significant whitespace.</li>
      </ul>
    </article>
  </section>
  <section class="main-section" id="syntax_basics">
    <header>Syntax Basics</header>
    <article>
      <p>Python syntax is designed to be intuitive and its code easy to read. Below is an example of a simple Python script:</p>
      <code>print("Hello, World!")</code>
      <p>Indentation is used to define code blocks in Python. For example:</p>
      <code>if 5 > 2: print("Five is greater than two")</code>
      <p>Python does not use curly braces ({}) to define code blocks like many other languages. Instead, it relies on indentation levels to determine the block structure.</p>
    </article>
  </section>
  <section class="main-section" id="data_types">
    <header>Data Types</header>
    <article>
      <p>Python supports various data types, including:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Numbers: int, float, complex</li>
        <li>Strings: str</li>
        <li>Boolean: bool</li>
        <li>Lists: list</li>
        <li>Dictionaries: dict</li>
        <li>Tuples: tuple</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Below is an example of defining different data types in Python:</p>
      <code>
        my_string = "Hello"
        my_int = 10
        my_float = 20.5
        my_list = [1, 2, 3]
      </code>
      <p>Python's dynamic typing allows you to change the data type of a variable as the program runs.</p>
    </article>
  </section> 
  <section class="main-section" id="control_structures">
    <header>Control Structures</header>
    <article>
      <p>Python includes several control structures for decision-making and looping, such as:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>If statements</li>
        <li>For loops</li>
        <li>While loops</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Example of an if-else statement in Python:</p>
      <code>
        age = 18
        if age >= 18:
        print("You are an adult.")
        else:
        print("You are still young.")
      </code>
    </article>
  </section>
  <section class="main-section" id="functions">
    <header>Functions</header>
    <article>
      <p>Functions in Python are defined using the <code>def</code> keyword. Functions can take arguments and return values.</p>
      <p>Here's an example of a simple Python function:</p>
      <code>
        def greet(name):
        return f"Hello, {name}!"
        print(greet("Alice"))
      </code>
      <p>Functions help organize code into reusable blocks and improve code readability.</p>
    </article>
  </section>
</main>
</body>
</html>

